WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.419 --> 00:00:12.470
&gt;&gt;Janis Bell: Thanks, I'm happy that so many
of you are interested in talking grammar and

00:00:12.470 --> 00:00:13.470
punctuation.

00:00:13.470 --> 00:00:14.929
I'm going to tell you briefly, or as an overview,
what my book addresses. And it doesn't address

00:00:14.929 --> 00:00:17.980
grammar from the ground up. It's not everything
anybody ever learned about grammar or needs

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:18.980
to know.

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:25.540
It covers just the mistakes that people usually
make or the problems that they usually encounter

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:28.050
in the sentences that they write. And it really
doesn't matter what you're writing whether

00:00:28.050 --> 00:00:35.030
you're writing for business or you're writing
an email to a friend or you're writing something,

00:00:35.030 --> 00:00:39.370
an academic paper. I mean sentences are sentences.
Fiction doesn't count; poetry doesn't count;

00:00:39.370 --> 00:00:45.129
you can do what you want, you're home free.
But when you're writing about situations that

00:00:45.129 --> 00:00:49.280
have occurred or are occurring or will occur,
then grammar and punctuation do count.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:58.459
So I'll tell you how my book progresses.

00:00:58.459 --> 00:01:01.510
It has seven chapters. Now let me start at
the end.

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:06.840
The seventh chapter is on punctuation and
it describes every mark that you'll need when

00:01:06.840 --> 00:01:14.140
you write in business correspondence or for
your school papers or whatever emails to friends.

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:17.710
It tells you what the marks do and what they
won't do.

00:01:17.710 --> 00:01:23.000
It tells you the common mistakes that people
make; the confusion that people have sometimes

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.659
between a semicolon and a colon, for example,
or between a dash and a hyphen.

00:01:28.659 --> 00:01:33.890
That's, that's a very common confusion that
I run into; people typing a hyphen and thinking

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:46.210
that it's a dash. You know what I'm talking
about? A hyphen is the smallest horizontal

00:01:46.210 --> 00:01:49.759
line that you can find on your keyboard and
in order to create a dash, which is a very

00:01:49.759 --> 00:01:52.340
different mark you need to hit that hyphen
key twice typically. Sometimes it closes up

00:01:52.340 --> 00:01:54.890
on the screen, sometimes it doesn't. But that,
that's a dash and it does something very different

00:01:54.890 --> 00:01:55.890
from what hyphens do.

00:01:55.890 --> 00:02:01.391
So people do run into confusion when it comes
to punctuation. As a matter of fact, I would

00:02:01.391 --> 00:02:05.590
say most people couldn't tell you how to use
a comma. Certainly in some sentences we know

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:10.240
where commas belong, but questions arise.
People typically ask, "Well do you need the

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:16.770
comma before 'and' when you have three or
more items in a series?" In the writing that

00:02:16.770 --> 00:02:20.220
you're reading, the professional writing that
has been professionally written and edited,

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:22.459
sometimes you'll see that comma and sometimes
you won't. I don't know whether you pay attention

00:02:22.459 --> 00:02:25.780
to that kind of thing, of course I do.

00:02:25.780 --> 00:02:30.160
But that can be confusing. You know, how come
Time Magazine is not putting it in and the

00:02:30.160 --> 00:02:34.800
New Yorker is putting it in? If you take a
look at sentences that contain items in a

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:35.800
series.

00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:41.040
The rule is, just to answer that question
right now, that you do put it in. That it

00:02:41.040 --> 00:02:44.750
gives equal attention to all the items in
a series without making the last two look

00:02:44.750 --> 00:02:51.580
more related than any others. That's the tradition,
that's the original rule. Many publications

00:02:51.580 --> 00:02:55.580
follow it and yet some authors and editors
and publications are choosing not to follow

00:02:55.580 --> 00:03:00.950
it. So that's why you see it both ways. I
follow the rule. I, I think it makes sense;

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:05.599
not just because I like rules, although I
do; but because it makes sense in that it

00:03:05.599 --> 00:03:12.220
gives every item equal attention and there's
no lack of clarity communicating that the

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:16.720
last two items are somehow more related than
the first two, or the first three, anyhow.

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:23.520
So the last chapter does cover all the typical
questions and issues that arise with the different

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:24.520
punctuation marks.

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:29.719
But the rest of the book; the first six chapters
are about grammar and usage.

00:03:29.719 --> 00:03:36.400
You know there are certain ways in which we
use words that are not strictly a grammar

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:40.950
matter, but a usage matter. Let me be more
specific. Sometimes with prepositions, you

00:03:40.950 --> 00:03:44.370
know those little words like "of," "to," "from,"
"around," "about," "above," "beyond," "below,"

00:03:44.370 --> 00:03:45.750
"past," "by," "under," "over," those little
words?

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:54.340
We have a lot of idioms. For example we can
be confused "by" something, we can be confused

00:03:54.340 --> 00:03:58.079
"over" something, I believe, I'm probably
acceptable, but we can't be confused "to"

00:03:58.079 --> 00:04:02.720
something. Now that's not grammar. I mean
the grammar's the same with those three examples.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:08.239
But the usage is not. I mean it's just that
we're never confused "to" are we? We're confused

00:04:08.239 --> 00:04:12.080
"by," we're concerned "over," sometimes we
can be confused, oh "in relation to" and we

00:04:12.080 --> 00:04:18.109
can have all kinds of connecting words that
follow "confused," but "to" isn't one of them.

00:04:18.109 --> 00:04:21.800
So my book does cover a couple of usage issues
too.

00:04:21.800 --> 00:04:26.440
The first chapter covers case. I'm sorry to
use this grammar term and I'll tell you what

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:33.590
it is. I did use regular grammar terms because
if I had to replace them I would have to use

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:36.171
words like "hot dog" and "hamburger" and then
you'd have to remember throughout the book

00:04:36.171 --> 00:04:40.420
that a, a "hot dog" is an adjective and a
"hamburger" is an adverb and it seemed to

00:04:40.420 --> 00:04:43.310
me just the same trouble, so I used the regular
words.

00:04:43.310 --> 00:04:51.600
Case refers to forms of pronouns. You know,
is it "I" is it "me" is it "myself?" Right?

00:04:51.600 --> 00:04:58.160
"Steven invited Susan and I to dinner." No.
"Steven invited Susan and me to dinner. " Yes.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:03.010
Susan, "Steven invited Susan and myself to
dinner," which is a very common error these

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:06.910
days using myself when it should be "I" or
when it should be "me." That's not correct

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:12.600
either. When do we use "myself?" Well that's
the kind of thing that Chapter One does cover.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.850
Chapter Two is called, "Agreement" and it
has to do with subjects and verbs. You remember

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:22.460
those? And agreement refers to number. So
if the subject is plural the verb has to be

00:05:22.460 --> 00:05:27.720
in a plural form. If the subject is singular,
etc. Sounds pretty simple and basic; you learned

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:29.300
it a long time ago; you get it right most
of the time.

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:34.400
But there are situations that confuse us or
situations that we don't handle correctly.

00:05:34.400 --> 00:05:38.240
We aren't even confused; we just don't know
what's goin' on.

00:05:38.240 --> 00:05:47.390
There are some nouns that are singular and
plural in Latin ways that not everybody's

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:51.670
familiar with; for example, "media." You know
very few people are handling that right these

00:05:51.670 --> 00:05:59.500
days. "Media" is plural. "The media are represented
here today." And the singular is "medium."

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:06.800
Of course nobody talks about a newspaper correspondent
as coming from a "medium," but that is the

00:06:06.800 --> 00:06:07.800
singular.

00:06:07.800 --> 00:06:13.000
Another common confusion is over "criteria"
and "criterion." The "o-n" word again is singular

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.600
and "criteria" is plural. And yet you hear
people saying, "There's one criteria that

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:21.330
we must follow here." Right? And I always
think, "Oh my goodness sake."

00:06:21.330 --> 00:06:26.420
So there are words like that. "Data" is another
one. "Data" is actually plural and so it should

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:33.580
be the "data are" not the "data is." And that
chapter on agreement covers that kind of issue.

00:06:33.580 --> 00:06:37.570
What's really plural, what's really singular.

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:42.440
There are many words in our language that
never take an "s," and yet they can represent

00:06:42.440 --> 00:06:48.460
groups, right? Many elements like "information"
and "jewelry" and "advice" and "furniture."

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:52.100
And if English is your native tongue you know
that automatically. Nobody had to teach you

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:56.020
that, you've never heard those words with
an "s" on the end. So it's easy to select

00:06:56.020 --> 00:06:57.200
the right verb.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:07:01.800
But if it's not your native tongue, imagine
it's difficult to come to a language where

00:07:01.800 --> 00:07:06.110
usually you can put an "s" on the end of the
word and make it plural. And yet there are

00:07:06.110 --> 00:07:11.430
all these exceptions. So if it's not your
native tongue and you're rather new to English,

00:07:11.430 --> 00:07:17.940
"advices" probably sounds fine to you. "Informations"
probably not. "Jewelrys," "furnitures," probably.

00:07:17.940 --> 00:07:23.200
So the book does address issues like that
too that crop up for non-native speakers,

00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:27.490
but primarily it's for native speakers; it's
for educated native speakers; it's for people

00:07:27.490 --> 00:07:32.690
who know their language as you do and have
to write.

00:07:32.690 --> 00:07:38.860
When we speak we of course make mistakes.
Speaking is a much more rapid activity. We

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:45.770
just don't have the time to think about the
proper grammar and usage beforehand. And when

00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:48.960
we speak we have a lot more going for us then
when we write. We have facial expressions,

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:54.030
we've got this hand that waves around and
the other one that holds the microphone. We've,

00:07:54.030 --> 00:07:59.250
we've got going for us that we are speaking
at our own pace and the reader, or excuse

00:07:59.250 --> 00:08:03.900
me, the listener is trying to follow us and
so that person doesn't have a lot of time

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:07.430
to think about our grammar or our word choice
[laughs] because they're busy keeping up just

00:08:07.430 --> 00:08:08.970
trying to get the message.

00:08:08.970 --> 00:08:15.690
And yet when we write we have a lot more time
to create what the message is. And the reader

00:08:15.690 --> 00:08:20.770
has a lot more time to get it. The reader's
going at his or her pace.

00:08:20.770 --> 00:08:24.670
Ah, there's something else that crops up in
the agreement chapter. Pronouns have to agree

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:29.780
with an earlier noun. I just said, "The reader
is going at his or her pace," and that gets

00:08:29.780 --> 00:08:34.950
kind of cumbersome, huh? And yet you can't
just pretend the whole world is male anymore.

00:08:34.950 --> 00:08:39.659
Well, it probably was never so that you could
pretend it in your life time, but in my life

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:45.279
time, in the beginning, in writing the masculine
pronoun was perfectly acceptable and that's

00:08:45.279 --> 00:08:50.129
all you ever saw. But there are ways around
that, and the second chapter does address

00:08:50.129 --> 00:08:51.439
them.

00:08:51.439 --> 00:08:56.060
Anytime you get into that "he," "she," "him,"
"her," "his," "her" bind you have to realize

00:08:56.060 --> 00:09:01.050
it's because you're the one who chose to say
"reader" earlier in that sentence, or "visitor"

00:09:01.050 --> 00:09:06.399
or "listener" or "user." Right? If you go
back and make that word plural "readers,"

00:09:06.399 --> 00:09:10.290
"visitors," "listeners," "users" then you
can follow it up with "they" and "them" and

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:13.529
"their" and you're out of the "he/she" bind.

00:09:13.529 --> 00:09:15.009
[pause]

00:09:15.009 --> 00:09:18.879
The third chapter's on verb tense and native
speakers of English don't have that many problems

00:09:18.879 --> 00:09:22.769
with tense. It's just automatic, we use present
when we need it, past when we need it, future

00:09:22.769 --> 00:09:26.560
when we need it. We know how to form them.
We've been hearing them our whole lives. But

00:09:26.560 --> 00:09:33.199
we do have some problems with verb tense and
those are represented here.

00:09:33.199 --> 00:09:38.740
For example, if you read an article yesterday
you'd be inclined to write or say about it

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:44.329
that the article "reported" something, right?
And yet that article is still reporting something.

00:09:44.329 --> 00:09:49.750
It's that you read it yesterday and that past
tense is in your memory and so you are saying

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:54.690
that the article "reported that Google did
something." Well it could be that Google did

00:09:54.690 --> 00:09:58.639
something in the past, but the article is
still reporting it. So that really should

00:09:58.639 --> 00:10:02.930
be present tense. "The article reports" that
Google did something. Kind of interesting.

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:08.259
Those are the kinds of issues that native
speakers have with tense and those crop up

00:10:08.259 --> 00:10:09.259
in Chapter Three.

00:10:09.259 --> 00:10:15.139
Let's see, case, agreement, tense. Mood. There's
something called "mood" in grammar. Not a

00:10:15.139 --> 00:10:19.879
good mood or a bad mood, but specifically
a subjunctive mood. Never mind you really

00:10:19.879 --> 00:10:23.250
don't need the terminology. Let me tell you
what it translates into.

00:10:23.250 --> 00:10:30.069
When we're speculating about something, we
have a choice. We are trying to convey to

00:10:30.069 --> 00:10:35.800
the listener or the reader that either what
we're speculating about is possible or what

00:10:35.800 --> 00:10:39.459
we're speculating about is impossible, but
we're speculating anyway.

00:10:39.459 --> 00:10:48.639
For example, "If I were from Los Angeles I
would be chilly up here." "If I were from

00:10:48.639 --> 00:10:54.920
Los Angeles I would be chilly up here." You
can hear from my verbs "were" and "would"

00:10:54.920 --> 00:11:01.690
that I'm not from Los Angeles, right? Now
if I change that sentence and, and say, "If

00:11:01.690 --> 00:11:08.560
Carol is from Los Angeles she is surely chilly
up here," now you probably get the message

00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:14.560
that it's possible that Carol's from Los Angeles.
"If Carol is from Los Angeles she is probably

00:11:14.560 --> 00:11:19.720
chilly up here." Do you hear it? It's possible
that she's from LA. Can you hear that possibility?

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:25.259
Let me change the other sentence back into
Carol because it should be consistent. I started

00:11:25.259 --> 00:11:30.250
with "I." The reason I had switched over to
"Carol" is if I don't know whether Carol's

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:36.449
from Los Angeles but its possible, then I
can use "is." If she "is" from Los Angeles

00:11:36.449 --> 00:11:43.550
then she "is" probably chilly, right? But
I can't speculate that way about me. I know

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:47.079
where I'm from. So that's why I had to switch
over to "Carol." Do you see?

00:11:47.079 --> 00:11:51.769
So let me put her in the subjunctive. "If
Carol were from Los Angeles she would be chilly

00:11:51.769 --> 00:11:57.499
up here." Now you should be getting the message
that she's not from LA, right? If she "were"

00:11:57.499 --> 00:12:04.300
from LA she would do something. If she "is"
from LA she "is" probably a certain way. The

00:12:04.300 --> 00:12:08.689
sentence involving "were" and "would" should
be conveying the message to you that it's

00:12:08.689 --> 00:12:14.480
not happening. I'm speculating about it anyway,
but it's not happening. It's contrary to fact.

00:12:14.480 --> 00:12:18.689
And the other sentence should be conveying
to you that it's possible. I just don't know.

00:12:18.689 --> 00:12:26.370
"If she is a dancer, she probably needs money."
"If she were a dancer she would need money."

00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:29.050
You hear the difference?

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:30.050
[pause]

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:34.809
That's what this chapter addresses because
typical native speakers don't understand that

00:12:34.809 --> 00:12:38.100
we're supposed to be using "were." They're
using "was" in all those situations. They

00:12:38.100 --> 00:12:43.120
know they're speculating, but they're using
"was." You know, "If I was there." Well are

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:47.410
you there? No. You're speculating about something
that isn't possible, right? So if I "were"

00:12:47.410 --> 00:12:48.579
there not if I "was" there.

00:12:48.579 --> 00:12:53.709
Do we have to worry about this with every
sentence? No. There are just certain words

00:12:53.709 --> 00:13:00.870
that lead to speculation. "If" is one of 'em.
Everyone sentence involving "if" can be speculating

00:13:00.870 --> 00:13:05.360
about something that's not true or speculating
about something that could be true.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:09.860
"Wish" is another one. "Wish" always leads
to a statement that's contrary to fact or

00:13:09.860 --> 00:13:12.649
you wouldn't be "wishing." "I wish I were."
"She wishes he were."

00:13:12.649 --> 00:13:13.699
[pause]

00:13:13.699 --> 00:13:21.290
No matter who's "wishing" the verb should
be "were." It shouldn't be "was." So the chapter

00:13:21.290 --> 00:13:22.649
addresses that.

00:13:22.649 --> 00:13:26.829
The next one's on modifiers; a real fancy
term for words that describe. And you might

00:13:26.829 --> 00:13:31.559
say, "Oh that's easy. Words that describe,
adjectives, right?" How many of them are adjectives

00:13:31.559 --> 00:13:35.889
in fact, but in forms that you were never
told are adjectives?

00:13:35.889 --> 00:13:40.519
For example, if I say, "While driving down
the freeway," would you believe that, that,

00:13:40.519 --> 00:13:46.389
that whole phrase is an adjective? I'm describing
somebody who's driving down the freeway and

00:13:46.389 --> 00:13:53.369
the word in that opening phrase that is the
descriptive word is the word "driving." So

00:13:53.369 --> 00:13:57.809
when an opening phrase has an action word,
like "running," "walking," "swimming," "dancing,"

00:13:57.809 --> 00:14:01.949
"driving," "researching," "analyzing," "deciding,"
it doesn't matter; that word is trying to

00:14:01.949 --> 00:14:07.839
describe somebody or something. It's usually
a somebody and whoever it is has to follow

00:14:07.839 --> 00:14:09.839
the phrase.

00:14:09.839 --> 00:14:12.999
Let me give you an example and you'll know
that you're gut understands this before your

00:14:12.999 --> 00:14:18.600
head does. "Crawling across the yard the snail
intrigued the baby." Who's crawling?

00:14:18.600 --> 00:14:20.630
[pause]

00:14:20.630 --> 00:14:26.029
"Crawling across the yard the snail intrigued
the baby." Who's crawling? The snail. You

00:14:26.029 --> 00:14:30.520
should, well you should think it's the snail.
You have a good imagination if you think it's

00:14:30.520 --> 00:14:36.519
the baby. The baby came later. "Crawling across
the yard the snail," hear it? "Intrigued the

00:14:36.519 --> 00:14:39.559
baby." So you should be thinking it's the
snail that's doing the crawling. On the other

00:14:39.559 --> 00:14:45.309
hand, if I change it and put the baby next
to the crawling phrase, then you'll be right

00:14:45.309 --> 00:14:47.269
to assume that it's the kid who's crawling.

00:14:47.269 --> 00:14:53.440
"Crawling across the yard the baby followed
the snail."

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:55.100
[pause]

00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:58.899
"Crawling across the yard the baby pursued
the snail." Let me change the verb; make it

00:14:58.899 --> 00:15:02.889
a little more interesting. "Crawling across
the yard the baby pursued the snail." You

00:15:02.889 --> 00:15:06.369
should be understanding that now it's the
baby that's crawling across the yard.

00:15:06.369 --> 00:15:11.150
Whoever I put next to that crawling phrase
is gonna wind up crawling. Unless I put a

00:15:11.150 --> 00:15:15.970
word there that doesn't crawl and then the
reader goes, "What?" And so maybe the reader

00:15:15.970 --> 00:15:19.980
figures it out because he understands the
context and he understands who can crawl and

00:15:19.980 --> 00:15:25.509
who can't. Still it's not a good sentence
and it's not a sentence that most of us were

00:15:25.509 --> 00:15:31.629
taught about anytime in high school or middle
school or grammar school or even college.

00:15:31.629 --> 00:15:37.750
I could have a Ph.D. in English today and
not understand that kind of sentence structure.

00:15:37.750 --> 00:15:42.459
And the only reason I really understand all
of these things is that I, during my graduate

00:15:42.459 --> 00:15:46.149
studies focused on the teaching of writing.
It's amazing isn't it?

00:15:46.149 --> 00:15:50.689
But anyway, it's that kind of thing that crops
up in the mod, modifiers chapter.

00:15:50.689 --> 00:15:54.730
There's another really popular one people
saying "like I said," "like I told you." And

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:58.360
that really should be "as I said" and "as
I told you." And of course there's a place

00:15:58.360 --> 00:16:04.259
for "like" but not in that particular phrase,
and that chapter explains that.

00:16:04.259 --> 00:16:08.050
After that the sixth grammar chapter's on
connectives; words that connect. We've got

00:16:08.050 --> 00:16:13.040
prepositions, as I mentioned it before. You
know the "in," "on," "to," "from." The key

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:17.730
question that usually pops us is, is it against
the rule to end a sentence in a preposition?

00:16:17.730 --> 00:16:22.110
And I think that's about all anybody ever
remembers about prepositions at that, at some

00:16:22.110 --> 00:16:26.679
point somebody told them not to end a sentence
in one. Yet, it's fine to do so as long as

00:16:26.679 --> 00:16:31.790
there's a word earlier in the sentence that
goes with that preposition. It's pretty awkward

00:16:31.790 --> 00:16:35.389
to always tuck them back in. You can ruin
a whole idiom.

00:16:35.389 --> 00:16:40.059
For example, "There were, there are certain
things up with which I will not put." I mean

00:16:40.059 --> 00:16:44.250
who writes like that? Who speaks like that?
The idiom is "to put up with." "There are

00:16:44.250 --> 00:16:48.100
certain things that I won't put up with."
Okay, that sentence ends in a preposition.

00:16:48.100 --> 00:16:52.980
So what? It's grammatically correct. It's
a stylistic choice whether you tuck it in

00:16:52.980 --> 00:16:56.959
or put it at the end.

00:16:56.959 --> 00:17:02.100
And certainly conjunctions are connectives
too, and, and there are a couple of kinds

00:17:02.100 --> 00:17:06.510
of conjunctions and they change the structure
of a sentence. And your punctuation options

00:17:06.510 --> 00:17:09.300
are different depending on the kind of conjunction
you're using.

00:17:09.300 --> 00:17:12.930
And then there are words very common in the
business world, that are not conjunctions

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:17.790
at all and many people don't realize that.
They're words like "however," "furthermore,"

00:17:17.790 --> 00:17:25.660
"nevertheless," "moreover," "besides," "also."
Some of them are small; some of them are larger.

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:32.021
They can show the relationship between two
ideas and they can occur right in the middle

00:17:32.021 --> 00:17:38.960
of two sentences, but you need more than a
comma to connect those two ideas. Because

00:17:38.960 --> 00:17:43.620
those particular words "however," "furthermore,"
"therefore," "nevertheless," "moreover" they're

00:17:43.620 --> 00:17:47.330
not conjunctions. They don't have glue on
them. They're just transition words. They

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:52.240
have meaning; they're wonderful to use stylistically,
and as I say they're very popular in the business

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:58.050
world, but after the first idea the minimum
punctuation you should have is a semicolon.

00:17:58.050 --> 00:18:04.040
For example, "I enjoy teaching; however, I'm
not gonna do it for the rest of my life."

00:18:04.040 --> 00:18:08.860
Oh. The most common error that I've seen over
the last 35 years of teaching is that people

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:14.280
put a comma before and after that "however."
"I enjoy teaching" comma, "however" comma,

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:18.390
"I'm not gonna do it for the rest of my life."
And that is not Kosher, it's not allowable,

00:18:18.390 --> 00:18:23.130
it's not a stylistic option. You don't have
a glue word in the middle. You have a transition

00:18:23.130 --> 00:18:28.050
word. It shows the relationship between the
two ideas, but it doesn't join them.

00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:31.990
So all you can really do if you want those
two ideas in the same sentence is to put a

00:18:31.990 --> 00:18:37.700
semicolon after the first idea. And, yes,
there will be a comma after the "however"

00:18:37.700 --> 00:18:43.760
or the "furthermore" or the "therefore" because
they are introductory words. They're introducing

00:18:43.760 --> 00:18:47.120
the second idea. Your only other option is
to put a period. You can make two sentences

00:18:47.120 --> 00:18:51.950
out of 'em, but people know that. What people
don't understand is that these words don't

00:18:51.950 --> 00:18:56.800
join ideas and so if you want the two ideas
in the same sentence, you still need some

00:18:56.800 --> 00:19:01.000
glue and the semicolon is that glue.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.710
So that kind of thing is in the connectives
chapter.

00:19:04.710 --> 00:19:08.900
Also the notion of parallel structure's in
there; meaning items in a series have to match

00:19:08.900 --> 00:19:13.490
because whenever you have connecting words,
what you connecting, words or phrases or whole

00:19:13.490 --> 00:19:16.150
ideas? And they have to match each other.

00:19:16.150 --> 00:19:22.780
So you, of course, may not write "Mary Jane
enjoys hiking, baking, and to ski." That's

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:26.900
an error in parallel structure. Items in a
series have to all be parallel, right? And

00:19:26.900 --> 00:19:31.030
you may be sitting there thinking, "Oh, easy
I would never write 'Mary Jane enjoys hiking,

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:35.550
baking, and to ski.'" No because those words
are close together and your ear wouldn't allow

00:19:35.550 --> 00:19:40.430
it. But when you add more words into the sentence,
which is more typical of business writing

00:19:40.430 --> 00:19:44.170
certainly, your ear doesn't always catch the
problem.

00:19:44.170 --> 00:19:48.550
So it could be "Mary Jane enjoys hiking on
Mt. Tamalpais in the springtime, baking cookies

00:19:48.550 --> 00:19:53.710
whenever it rains, and to ski at Lake Tahoe
in the winter." You see? The ear doesn't catch

00:19:53.710 --> 00:19:57.980
it right away. Your ear may be catching it
and you have an excellent ear. Or you may

00:19:57.980 --> 00:20:01.520
be aware of the error because I just gave
you the simplified version of it and you're

00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:07.410
lookin' for it. But typically when more words
are involved in each of the items people aren't

00:20:07.410 --> 00:20:11.910
so sensitive to whether they match each other.
And we really should be.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:16.310
I just used the word "whether" which reminds
me of another connective issue. Native speakers

00:20:16.310 --> 00:20:22.750
of English are always using "if" when we should
be using "whether," typical mistake? "We need

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:26.580
to know 'if' we're gonna proceed with this
project?" No. "We need to know whether we're

00:20:26.580 --> 00:20:32.270
gonna proceed with this project." Why? Because
when "or not" is understood, when the word

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:36.670
"or not" can be placed into the sentence,
you don't have to write it and you don't have

00:20:36.670 --> 00:20:37.700
to say it.

00:20:37.700 --> 00:20:43.170
But when you can place it in there that means
the connecting word you need is "whether."

00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:50.150
So "We need to know whether 'or not' we're
going to proceed with this project." Not "if."

00:20:50.150 --> 00:20:56.130
"If" sets up a condition. "If we proceed with
this project we're gonna need more money."

00:20:56.130 --> 00:21:01.640
In other words, upon a certain condition "we're
gonna need more money." So that distinction

00:21:01.640 --> 00:21:04.480
is also made in the connectives chapter.

