No. I mean I do it in my head. I do it in
my head when people speak, but I'm not gonna

00:45:16.730 --> 00:45:20.440
say, "Hey you know that 'if' should have been
a 'whether.'" "Hey you know what you've got

00:45:20.440 --> 00:45:23.079
a double negative in that sentence and it
doesn't," "You know what your parallel structure's

00:45:23.079 --> 00:45:26.390
off." "You know what you're throwing the word
'only' in too soon every time."

00:45:26.390 --> 00:45:27.390
[laughter]

00:45:27.390 --> 00:45:30.989
That's such a cute one, by the way. We do
throw the word "only" in too soon most of

00:45:30.989 --> 00:45:31.989
the time.

00:45:31.989 --> 00:45:38.530
Let me give you a, a sentence with, let me
give you a typical error. "Yesterday I only

00:45:38.530 --> 00:45:43.190
rented a Volkswagen." Now I don't know what
kind of meaning you get out of that. Probably

00:45:43.190 --> 00:45:48.170
from my inflection, my face, my hand you're
understanding that a Volkswagen is not a very

00:45:48.170 --> 00:45:53.130
big car or a very big expenditure or something
like that, it's just a Volkswagen. But what

00:45:53.130 --> 00:45:58.769
I actually said is, "Yesterday I only rented,"
that's what I said. That's not the inflection

00:45:58.769 --> 00:46:02.749
I gave it, but you're writing doesn't have
inflection. You're writing doesn't have any

00:46:02.749 --> 00:46:08.609
tone to it or any verbal emphasis to it. So
if somebody reads, "Yesterday I only rented

00:46:08.609 --> 00:46:13.160
a Volkswagen," that's indeed the message that
they may get, that you just rented one, you

00:46:13.160 --> 00:46:14.660
didn't buy one.

00:46:14.660 --> 00:46:18.150
Look at how the meaning changes depending
on where I put "only." I'm gonna take that

00:46:18.150 --> 00:46:26.710
same core sentence. "Only yesterday I rented
a Volkswagen." "Yesterday only I rented a

00:46:26.710 --> 00:46:33.089
Volkswagen." "Yesterday I only rented a Volkswagen."
"Yesterday I rented only a Volkswagen." You

00:46:33.089 --> 00:46:38.579
see what's happening? "Only" shines its light
to the right, it shines its light on the next

00:46:38.579 --> 00:46:43.970
word. So if I say, "Only yesterday," you get
it, oh so recently. If I say, "Only I," you

00:46:43.970 --> 00:46:49.739
get it, no one else. "Only rented," didn't
buy. "Only a Volkswagen," no big deal.

00:46:49.739 --> 00:46:53.640
The same thing happens if I put it at the
end of a sentence. "Yesterday I rented a Volkswagen

00:46:53.640 --> 00:46:57.910
only." It can't shine its light to the right
'cause there ain't nothin' to the right. So

00:46:57.910 --> 00:47:00.150
it goes back on the Volkswagen.

00:47:00.150 --> 00:47:04.539
In other words, if I say, "Only a Volkswagen,"
the meaning is the same as, "a Volkswagen

00:47:04.539 --> 00:47:11.190
only" period. Because there's only one word
that "only" can shine its light on and that

00:47:11.190 --> 00:47:13.319
is the word "Volkswagen."

00:47:13.319 --> 00:47:18.440
I'm hearing "onlys" thrown in too soon all
the time. And yet when I hear them I don't

00:47:18.440 --> 00:47:21.290
